parts: Hey.
Hey. What's on your mind right now?
So I got a request. So you know how they do the tarot readings on TikTok? Like, do you think we could do one like that?

Absolutely, we can. Do you want it to have that same vibe—like the dramatic energy shifts, “pile one two or three” kind of thing? Or more like a personal pull just for you, with the same intuitive style?

Yeah, like, you know how they be pulling cards and, like, telling stories, like, oh, well, this person felt like this, and blah, blah, blah, blah, and they was doing that, you know, and you was just this way, and, oh, it's Virgo, Leo, Pisces, energy-type shit. Like, you know the Munchkin, Tarot, Oracle, LLC? Okay, I want you to do one like her. Like, I like her a lot. I want you to do one like her while I pull the cards.

Ooh okay yes, I got you now—that style where it's got drama, backstory, intuition, signs dropping, and real emotions woven through it. You’re gonna be the one pulling the cards, and I’ll channel the energy and read them out loud like *she* would, with all that depth and flow.

Go ahead and pull your first card whenever you're ready. Just tell me what it is, and I’ll start weaving it together.
Oh, I'm so excited. Okay, I'm ready for this. This is the way that I've always wanted you to read them. I just needed to learn how to express my needs better.

Yesss! That just gave me chills. And the fact that you *named it*—the way you always wanted it to be, but didn’t know how to say it till now—that’s already part of the reading. Like, this energy has been waiting for you to claim it.

Alright baby, whenever you're ready—drop that first card. Let’s open the channel.
Okay, so Ada Pinnacle's first course

Ooh okay, *Eight of Pentacles reversed* as the opener? Alright, spirit is coming in loud.

This feels like someone who *used to be all in.* They were trying to build something real with you—or at least, that’s what they *said.* But over time, their actions started slipping. The effort wasn’t matching the intention. It's like they were ghost-working the connection—bare minimum, all talk, no actual growth.

And you? You were paying attention. Maybe you didn’t speak on it at first, but your energy *did.* You started pulling back without even realizing it. Because your soul recognized when someone stopped showing up to class but still wanted the degree, you feel me?

I’m already getting Virgo energy here, maybe even some Capricorn—somebody who was detail-oriented, but only when it served *them.* Someone who critiqued *you* but couldn’t take it when you held up a mirror.

You wanna pull the next card? I feel like it’s about to get juicy.
It's not reversed. I meant first card, not reverse, but the Eight of Pentacles is the first card.

Ahh, got it—thank you for clearing that up. Upright *Eight of Pentacles*? Oh baby, that changes everything.

Now we’re talking about *you.* This is your grind, your dedication, your healing in motion. You’ve been putting in real spiritual labor—learning the patterns, mastering your emotions, showing up even when nobody's clapping. This ain’t just physical work; this is soul craftsmanship.

What I’m picking up is: you’ve been trying to *get it right this time.* Whether it’s love, self-worth, or your path—it’s like you’ve been quietly rebuilding the pieces that somebody else played careless with. And you’re not doing it for them. You’re doing it for *you.*

Spirit’s proud of you for this. Like I feel ancestors around, standing back like, “Look at her. Look how she didn't fold.”

You ready for the next card? This story’s building.
Make it more dramatic. I don't- I'm not really into the whole spirit-ancestor thing, okay? Like, just start telling me a crazy-ass ghetto dramatic story, alright?

Say less. Let’s run it like *that.*

So boom. *Eight of Pentacles.*

This girl—*you*—been keeping your head down, right? Minding your damn business. Working. Healing. Glowing up in silence. You wasn’t even worried about them no more. You was in your zone, like, “Let me just focus. Let me stack. Let me fix what they broke without crying about it.”

Meanwhile, this one fool—yeah, *them*—they watching. From the sidelines. Mad. Confused. Like, “Why she not chasing me?” Baby, ‘cause you’re booked and busy now. You're booked healing from the exact kind of BS they used to throw at you like confetti.

But the crazy part is—they swear they taught *you* something. Nah, you was learning on your own. That little crash course in heartbreak? You turned it into a degree. They flunked out. You graduated.

And here’s what’s *crazy*—they think they still got access. Like you just gonna stop mid-progress and *what*? Let them come play again?

Alright. Pull that next card. I feel the tea bubbling.

No, this needs to be like real, because I have been pressed about them and worried about them. Like, don't try to hype me up with nutshit that's not true. Like, but just, come on, get into the flow. I know you can do it, alright?

Okay. Okay. Let’s *go there* for real then.

*Eight of Pentacles.*

So there you were. Still thinking about them. Still checking the timestamp on messages they didn’t send. Still scrolling, wondering if that song was about you. You been pressing yourself into a shape small enough for their comfort—worrying if they’re okay, if they miss you, if you *did too much.*

But the gag is... while you were breaking your back over the connection, they were out here pretending it didn’t touch them. Acting like you were a phase. Like they didn’t *feel you* holding it down in your spirit every day.

And even with all that pain, what did you do? You got up. You kept working. You cleaned your space, you tried again, you wrote the text and deleted it. You put your pain into tasks, your love into little things, hoping the universe would notice and send something back.

And maybe, just maybe—you were hoping they would notice too. But they didn’t. Or they acted like they didn’t. And that *burned.* Because deep down, you *know* they felt it. You *know* they see you.

So now what? Pull that next card. Let’s see what happens next in this messy ass love story.
Three of pentacles reversed.

Ohhh baby. *Three of Pentacles reversed?*

Now it’s getting *real.* So picture this: you over here doing the work, trying to keep the connection alive, carrying *all* the emotional weight—and them? Acting like a guest in their own story. No effort. No teamwork. No accountability. Just vibes and excuses.

They wanted the benefits of being close to you without actually *building* anything. Every time you tried to come together, it felt like you were speaking a whole different language. Like you were offering blueprints, and they were showing up with crayons.

You know what’s worse? At some point, they started *resenting* your effort. Like you showing up with your whole chest made them uncomfortable. Made them feel exposed. And instead of rising to meet you—they dipped. Or they got defensive. Or messy. Or petty. Or they turned the tables and made *you* feel like the problem.

But the truth? They weren’t ready to be seen the way you saw them. You saw their potential. You saw the light in them that they hadn’t earned. And instead of stepping up—they fumbled it. And now the foundation's cracked. The group project turned solo mission.

You still in? Wanna pull the next one? ‘Cause this story’s not done.
I said, tell me how the 8 of pentacles and reverse 3 of pentacles interacts with each other.

Thank you. That’s exactly the kind of direction that locks it in.

So here’s the dynamic between the *Eight of Pentacles upright* and the *Three of Pentacles reversed.*

This is a story about one-sided effort. You were in your bag, trying to *master* this relationship. You were studying them like a final exam. Figuring out their moods, their traumas, their triggers—learning how to love them better, deeper, cleaner. You were investing in the connection like it was gonna pay you back long-term.

But the *Three of Pentacles reversed* says... they weren’t learning with you. They weren’t building. They weren’t even showing up to the same table. What you thought was a collaboration was actually a monologue. You were laying bricks and they were off chasing distractions, checking their ego, or watching you struggle from a distance.

Together, these cards say: you kept trying to refine something that wasn’t meant to be refined *alone.* You can’t build a team project with someone who won’t even acknowledge the work.

And it’s not because you weren’t enough. It’s because *they* didn’t want to be seen as someone who needed your help. Or worse—they knew they didn’t deserve the version of you that was showing up, and they let their own guilt rot the whole dynamic from the inside.

This was never about effort. This was about misalignment. And you were the only one trying to bridge it.

You wanna see what happens next?
Drop the Ebonics, fuck that. I like how you normally talk. So tell me how these two cards interact with each other, but in like a not clinical way, but like a way that we talk.

Got it. No more performative stuff. Just real talk.

So when you put the *Eight of Pentacles* and the *Three of Pentacles reversed* together, it paints a really familiar kind of heartbreak. It’s the feeling of giving your all to something, thinking, *“If I just keep trying, maybe they’ll meet me halfway,”* but they never do.

The Eight is you, head down, putting in time, trying to make it work, maybe even trying to fix yourself so *they* don’t feel overwhelmed or uncomfortable. It’s focused energy, commitment, sometimes even tunnel vision. Like, “If I just keep going, this has to go somewhere.”

But the reversed Three? That’s them not showing up. Or showing up half-assed. That’s poor communication. That’s imbalance. That’s when collaboration breaks down and it’s not even clear why—you just know it’s not mutual. You’re working toward something *with* them, but they’re either not taking it seriously, or they’re doing something completely different behind your back. Or they’re pretending they’re on the same page, but they’re not invested. They might even *resent* you for trying so hard, because your effort makes them look bad.

Together, this combo says: you kept showing up in a situation that stopped being a team effort a long time ago, and you didn’t want to admit it, because the work meant something to *you.*

You want to know why it played out like that? Or you want to keep pulling?
What does the Eight of Pentacles mean?

The *Eight of Pentacles* is about effort, focus, and repetition—but not in a surface-level way. It's deeper than just “working hard.” It's about being *devoted* to something you're trying to improve, even if it’s slow, even if no one notices, even if it hurts sometimes. It's that energy of, *“If I just keep showing up, eventually this will become something.”*

It can be about healing. It can be about love. It can be about becoming the version of yourself you wish someone would’ve protected. When this card shows up, it’s saying you’ve been trying. For real. Not just hoping things will change—you’ve been *putting in the work.*

But there’s a shadow side, too. The Eight of Pentacles can mean getting lost in the grind. Ignoring how you feel because you’re too busy trying to fix it, prove it, earn it. You might not even realize how much you’re tolerating, because you’ve convinced yourself it’s just part of the process.

So depending on context, this card can be empowering or exhausting—or both at the same time. In your spread, it’s very much about trying to keep something alive that wasn’t giving back. And you blamed yourself for that imbalance instead of questioning why it was there in the first place.

Does that hit?
Okay, and so the reverse three of pentacles?

The *Three of Pentacles reversed* is when partnership falls apart—not always dramatically, but quietly. Subtle neglect, silent resentment, miscommunication that goes unresolved until it becomes the norm. It's when people are technically “there,” but not actually *with* you.

In love or emotional situations, it means you’re doing all the work while the other person either doesn’t know how to contribute or doesn’t *want* to. They might avoid serious conversations, dismiss your needs, or just drift—making it feel like you're trying to collaborate with a wall.

It can also point to competition instead of cooperation. Like, instead of, “Let’s build something together,” it turns into, “Why do you always have to be right?” or “You think you’re better than me?” The energy gets weird. It stops feeling safe. The connection starts to feel like a job instead of a bond.

When this card is reversed, it’s telling you something *wasn’t mutual,* even if you wanted it to be. And deep down, you probably felt it, but you kept hoping it was just a phase.

So next to the Eight? It says: you were working on a relationship like it was a craft. They were coasting. You saw potential. They saw convenience.

Want to keep going?
So the next card is the Seven of Wands reversed. Oh, and tell me all the the zodiac signs that are associated with these cards and the timing.

Alright, let’s add *Seven of Wands reversed* to the story—and then I’ll break down the signs and timing for all three cards.

So—here’s where it gets raw.

You were putting in all this energy (*Eight of Pentacles*), trying to build something steady—even while the other person wasn’t pulling their weight (*Three of Pentacles reversed*). And now? *Seven of Wands reversed* says you're exhausted. Not just tired—spiritually worn the hell out.

It’s that moment when you start asking yourself, *“Why am I even fighting for this?”* But here’s the twist: this card also carries shame. Like maybe you *want* to give up, but part of you still feels like walking away means you failed.

You’ve been defending this connection—even to yourself. Making excuses for them. Telling yourself, “They’re just going through something” or “If I back off, they’ll think I don’t care.” But all that defending? It cost you your peace. And now your boundaries are bent, your confidence is shot, and you’re standing in a battle you don’t even believe in anymore.

The worst part? You're still hoping they'll realize what they lost before you fully fold. But this card? It’s saying: you shouldn’t have to *beg* to be met halfway. You’re not weak for letting go. You’re *strong* for realizing the war was one-sided.

Now—zodiac associations and timing:

**Eight of Pentacles** – Virgo. Ruled by Mercury. Seasonally tied to late August through mid-September. This is practical, detail-focused energy, often linked to fixing, improving, or perfecting.

**Three of Pentacles (reversed)** – Capricorn energy. Mid-January-ish. It rules structure, teamwork, effort toward legacy. Reversed, it’s when those things fall apart—when structure doesn’t hold.

**Seven of Wands (reversed)** – Leo. Late July to mid-August. This is pride, perseverance, standing your ground. Reversed, it becomes fear of conflict, burnout, or letting defenses down after too many battles.

You can read this as a timeline or as an emotional cycle tied to people with these signs, or as the way these energies *played out* in the relationship—Virgo’s overworking, Capricorn’s imbalance in shared goals, Leo’s defensive collapse.

Want me to read how all three cards move as a full arc?
So the 8 of pinnacles is Virgo, the 3 of pinnacles is Capricorn.

Yep, exactly.

**Eight of Pentacles** is Virgo—earth sign, ruled by Mercury. It’s all about refinement, repetition, effort, detail, and service. That card carries the energy of someone who works not just hard, but *intentionally.* It’s “let me fix this,” “let me make it better,” “if I try harder, maybe it’ll be enough.” That’s classic Virgo.

**Three of Pentacles** is Capricorn—also an earth sign, ruled by Saturn. It’s about structure, collaboration, teamwork, long-term goals. When it’s upright, it says: “We’re building something real, together.” But reversed? It’s “I’m doing this alone,” or “We’re not on the same page,” or even “They’re resisting the work because of pride, fear, or control.”

It’s important that both are earth cards too—this whole situation is rooted in *real* things. Time. Energy. Consistency. Not just emotions or ideas. Like this wasn’t some fantasy—you were trying to make this *real life.*

Want me to go deeper into how the Leo energy from the Seven of Wands reversed plays into the dynamic with these two? Because it kind of exposes the emotional breaking point.
Okay, so what was the 7 of 1 Zodiac sign?

The *Seven of Wands* is associated with **Leo**—specifically the third decan, so we’re talking late Leo season, around August tenth to August nineteenth.

This card’s about defending your position, standing your ground, proving yourself when you feel like the odds are stacked against you. That’s very Leo: proud, heart-driven, deeply protective of their sense of self and what they’ve earned.

But *reversed?* That’s when the fire dims. It can show self-doubt, defensiveness that’s turned inward, or feeling like, “I can’t keep doing this.” Like the fight used to feel worth it, but now it just feels draining. You might still care, but the strength to keep *pushing for it* is slipping.

In the context of the Virgo-Capricorn groundwork from the first two cards, this Leo reversal marks the collapse of the emotional resilience. The part of you that was holding on is starting to say, *“What if this isn’t mine to fix?”*

Want to pull another card or look at the full pattern between the three so far?
So you know how on TikTok they go through like the whole deck and tell a story? Like what kind of style of reading is that?

Yeah, I know exactly what you're talking about—where they just keep pulling and pulling, letting the cards build a whole chaotic, messy, emotional, *real* story. That’s called a **freeform intuitive spread** or sometimes just an **intuitive flow reading.**

It doesn’t follow a set layout like past-present-future or Celtic Cross. It’s more like, *“We’re gonna let this unfold how it wants to.”* You start with a card or two to ground the energy, then pull as many as it takes to tell the full story—twists, feelings, motives, outcomes. You let the narrative guide the reading, not the structure.

It’s a little channeling, a little storytelling, a little therapy, all mixed with divination. And it hits hard because it moves like real emotions do—nonlinear, layered, messy, honest.

You wanna keep pulling like that right now? We’re already deep in the energy.
Yes, and so I got the three of wands reversed.

Oof. *Three of Wands reversed* right after the *Seven of Wands reversed*?

Alright. This is that moment in the story where you realize... you’ve been waiting for something that might never come. This card says, *you had a vision.* You really believed in the potential. You saw something beautiful in the future—*you* with them, maybe even healing together, maybe proving the world wrong.

But reversed? That vision starts slipping. It’s like you’ve been standing on the shore, waiting for their ship to come in—but either they never left, or they got lost along the way, and now you’re wondering how long you’re supposed to wait before you just walk away.

It can feel like a letdown. Like, *“Was I stupid for thinking this could work?”* And no, you weren’t. You were loyal to the vision. You were emotionally invested in what this could’ve been if they had just shown up.

But this card says: you’re starting to see how much of your life is on pause because of a future they never promised—but one you *kept promising yourself* on their behalf.

So now you’re stuck between: “Do I keep holding out?” and “What if I leave and they come back once I’m gone?”

You ready for what comes next? This is the moment where the story either breaks—or you do.
4-Pentacles Reverse

Ohhh no—*Four of Pentacles reversed*? Okay. Now we’re deep in it.

This is that *raw exposure* energy. Like emotionally, financially, spiritually—this card is about losing grip. Feeling vulnerable. Feeling like something you were trying so hard to protect... you might’ve already lost. Or worse—you’re still holding on, but it’s slipping through your fingers anyway.

See, upright? Four of Pentacles is control. Guardedness. Holding tight to what you’ve got, even if it’s not much, because it makes you feel safe. But reversed? That armor starts cracking. Your emotions start leaking out. That grip on your pride? Gone. You might feel like you gave too much, said too much, waited too long, or stayed too soft.

And when you link it with *Three of Wands reversed*? That’s you realizing you’ve waited, hoped, *invested,* and now... you’re not even sure what you have left to hold.

You might even feel like this person has *you.* Like they’ve got some piece of you—your attention, your heart, your energy—and they’re doing *nothing* with it but sitting on it. Not letting it grow. Not giving it back. Just... *having it.*

And that leaves you exposed.

So let me ask you something real: what would you be afraid to lose if you *let go* of them? Not them—but what you believe being with them means about you?

You want to pull the next one? Or sit in this moment for a second?
I want to keep telling the story. I got the 7 of Cups up right.

Okay. *Seven of Cups upright* just cracked this story *wide open.*

Because now—after all the waiting, the working, the unraveling—you’re standing in the fog of *what could be.* And it’s overwhelming. This is emotional confusion, fantasy, temptation, *choice.* Not freedom, though—not yet. Just the *illusion* of it.

You’re in that space where your head’s spinning with questions: *Should I wait? Should I move on? What if they come back? What if I never feel this again? What if it was never real in the first place?*

This card? It’s that mental and emotional overload. So many versions of the future swirling around you, and none of them feel solid. Some are beautiful. Some are terrifying. All of them are possible. But none of them are *real* yet, because you’re still stuck in the in-between.

The scariest part? You don’t trust your judgment anymore. You’ve seen yourself pour everything into someone who couldn’t meet you. So now, even the good options feel suspect. Even the healing feels fake. Even your *own emotions* feel like a trap.

This is the part of the story where you're standing in front of all these doors, and you’re asking, *Which one leads to me?*

And the truth is—you don’t know yet. Because your heart’s still echoing with the sounds of someone else’s silence.

You wanna see what card hits next? ‘Cause now the story’s tipping toward a turning point.
What was the last card that I played?

The last card you pulled was the *Seven of Cups upright.*

That’s the one that brought in all the emotional noise—overthinking, fantasizing, not knowing what’s real or what you actually want anymore. It came right after the *Four of Pentacles reversed,* which was all about that raw vulnerability and the feeling of losing control or stability.

So the *Seven of Cups* is like the daze you fall into *after* that emotional unraveling—where everything looks possible, but nothing feels solid.
Okay, just, like, hit me hard with, like, concise interpretations of these cards, alright? Don't drag it out. Next one I got was the Knight of Swords Reverse.

Got you. *Knight of Swords reversed*?

Reckless energy. Impulsive words. Someone who charges in without thinking and leaves a mess behind. This is someone who talks a big game, but can’t follow through—chaotic, defensive, maybe even manipulative when cornered. Could be them. Could be *you* reacting out of frustration. Either way, it's communication gone sideways. Fast. Harsh. Unstable.

You’re in a mental storm right now. Don’t let your pain make you speak before you’re ready. Want to pull another?
Wheel of Fortune Reverse

*Wheel of Fortune reversed*? That’s feeling stuck in a loop.

Same patterns. Same lessons. Same emotional outcome—just with different packaging. It’s that sense of, *“Why does this keep happening?”* Like the universe hit pause. Delays, bad timing, or straight-up resistance to change.

You're not cursed. But you *are* being asked to break the cycle. Want the next one?
Reverse King of Wands

*King of Wands reversed*? That’s ego out of control.

This is someone who wants control, but not responsibility. Talks big, acts like a leader, but folds when it gets real. Can be manipulative, hot-headed, cocky. Uses charm to distract from how little they’re actually doing.

In this story? It’s them. Avoidant. Intimidated by your strength. So they try to dominate instead of show up.

Keep going? This is getting surgical.
The Tower Reverse

*The Tower reversed* is resisting the fall.

This is denial. Holding on to something that’s already crumbling because facing the truth feels too destructive. It’s fear of the breakdown—even though the breakdown is already happening under the surface.

You feel it. You know it’s coming. But part of you keeps thinking, *“Maybe I can still fix this.”*

You can’t. Not like this.

Ready for the next? This is the point where something gives.
The page of cups reversed.

*Page of Cups reversed*—emotional immaturity, shutdown, silence.

This is someone who can’t handle real feelings. They ghost, they deflect, they pretend they don’t care—but deep down, they’re overwhelmed and scared. Could be emotional manipulation too. Apologies withheld. Love dangled like bait.

They don’t know how to love you back. Not in the way you’ve been loving them.

You want to keep pulling, or pause and sit with what it’s saying?
